entry.content:
The generated return statement for array `FromJniType` cases is:
```
// _ret has type jobject
return jni_zero::ConvertArray<std::vector<int32_t>>::FromJniType(
    env,
    jni_zero::JavaParamRef<jintArray>(env, _ret));
```

This fails as the the `_ret` cannot be implicitly converted from `jobject` to a `jintArray`, see [example failure](https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/try/android_compile_dbg/1893543/overview).

Repro URL: https://deploy-preview-2--view-transitions.netlify.app/stack-navigator/mpa/
Chrome Version: All
Recording: Attached

The linked to demo is an MPA with three pages. There‚Äôs MPA View Transitions going on between the pages, but that‚Äôs not relevant here - it also triggers in Chrome Stable which has no Cross-Document View Transitions support.

When navigating from one page to the other, the custom cursor that is declared gets shown, as expected.

```css
* {
    cursor: url(/stack-navigator/shared/cursor.svg) 16 16, auto !important;
}
*:active {
  cursor: url(/stack-navigator/shared/cursor-active.svg) 16 16, auto !important;
}
```

However, when clicking the little back arrow in the UI - which triggers a `navigation.back()` behind the scenes ‚Äì the custom cursor no longer shows. Hit detection on the page still works though, as seen in the attached recording.

To get the custom cursor to show again, the user needs to actively click the page.

Noteworthy is that the same happens when using the UA back button: after doing so, the custom cursor is not shown.
However, when performing a chain of back-forwards-back clicks (using the UA back/forward buttons) the custom cursor does show on the first page.

This issue is possibly related to https://issues.chromium.org/40719480

Problem:
ui/base/x/x11_global_shortcut_listener.cc
bool XGlobalShortcutListener::RegisterAccelerator(KeyboardCode key_code,...) {
...
  auto keysym = XKeysymForWindowsKeyCode(key_code, false);
  auto keycode = connection_->KeysymToKeycode(keysym);
}
after XKeysymForWindowsKeyCode(...) and KeysymToKeycode(...), if the input argument key_code=0,  the value keycode will 
be transformed to an UnExpeced keycode!!! And an unexpected shortcut is registered.
On my Ubuntu 23.04/GNOME(X11),  keycode is transformed to 204 and will make Alt_L shortcut registered. Other OSs may be different, LMDE6 will be BackSpace.
We can use command "xmodmap -pk | grep ${KEYCODE}" to check keysym for KEYCODE.

To Reproduce:
My test code keysymbug.c(Attacehed), compile with "gcc -Wno-deprecated-declarations -o keysymbug keysymbug.c -lX11".
Run keysymbug(test code), will produce output:
src keycode(0x0)->keysym(0x0:(null))
keysym(0x0)->translated to keycode(204:0xcc)
!!!Warning: keycode 0 tranformed to valued keycode(204:0xcc)
You can use shell command 'xmodmap -pk| grep 204' find key meanging.
1: keycode(204:0xcc) ->transformed to keysym(0xffe9:Alt_L)
!!!Warning: keycode 0 transformed to meaningful keysym:(65513:0xffe9:Alt_L)

Solution:
add extra check:
@@ -86,6 +86,11 @@ bool XGlobalShortcutListener::RegisterAccelerator(KeyboardCode key_code,
   auto keysym = XKeysymForWindowsKeyCode(key_code, false);
   auto keycode = connection_->KeysymToKeycode(keysym);

+  // if key_code is 0, keycode may be transformed to unexpected key.
+  if (key_code == ui::KeyboardCode::VKEY_UNKNOWN && keysym == 0) {
+    return false;
+  }
+
